philosophical thinkers of all genders, men remain the movers and shakers in the Jamesian universe-while women exist primarily to support their endeavors and serve their needs. How could the philosophy of William James, a man devoted to Victorian ideals, be used to support feminism? Feminist Interpretations of William James lays out the elements of James's philosophy that are particularly problematic for feminism, offers a novel feminist approach to James's ethical philosophy, and takes up epistemic contestations in and with James's pragmatism. The results are surprising. In short, James's philosophy can prove useful for feminist efforts to challenge sexism and male privilege, in spite of James himself.In this latest installment of the Re-Reading the Canon series, contributors appeal to William James's controversial texts not simply as an exercise in feminist critique but in the service of feminism.Along with the editors, the contributors are Jeremy Carrette, Lorraine Code, Megan Craig, Susan Dieleman, Jacob L. Goodson, Maurice Hamington, Erin McKenna, José Medina, and Charlene Haddock Seigfried.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFeminist theory. 0aPragmatism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Pragmatism.2bisacsh1 aCarrette, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCode, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Megan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDieleman, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodson, Jacob L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamington, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKenna, Erin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMedina, José, econtribu